European inflation slipped into food
Accelerated inflation, recorded in the euro area, is primarily due to the dizzying rise in the price of food products.
The November price increase has been higher than expected in the 13 euro-zone countries, registering - after 2.6 percent in October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent - announced the Luxembourg-based Union Statistics Office.
Official forecasts were as likely as 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the U.S., British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut basic interest, on the pretext that the decline, along with rising commodity prices and a reduction in forced unemployment, would trigger a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in the 22:2 trap: “You have to negotiate” on inflation so that you don’t have to intervene on this issue later.
Germany’s 3.3 percent inflation broke the 12-year record, while Spain’s rose from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Inflation skyrocketed in the euro area as a result of rampant food and energy prices.
Quotas for wheat rose by 88 percent and soybeans also reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market rose this year by 52 percent, reaching nearly $100 a barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from 2.1 percent today to 2.5 percent, while by 2009 it will drop to 1.9.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain in the next 3 or 4 months around 3 percent, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to reduce interest rates twice during 2008.
Gallup predicts a government crisis
After a long stagnation, by early December the support of the Young Democrats Alliance increased significantly, reaching its peak level since 2002, while Gallup never before experienced such a low level – 13 percent – in the case of socialists.
The difference in the case of confident party voters – due to the greater firmness of opposition voters – would mean support of more than two-thirds (71 percent) versus support of one-fifth for socialists (20 percent).
According to the survey, the Democratic Forum and the Alliance of Free Democrats would not reach the necessary limit to have any parliamentary seat: their support within the entire population is two percent.
Among confident voters there are one percent more sympathizers on both sides.
The economic environment continued to deteriorate even compared to the previous low - it has never been so high, at 41 percent the proportion of those who deemed the economic situation of the country especially bad, while another 46 percent believe the situation is quite bad.
Families, after the most hopeful expectations of spring and summer, are now more pessimistic about changing their own economic situation.
As for next year, the majority of the population is deteriorating and only one-tenth expects improvement.
In December, 71 percent of respondents, higher than any previous Gallup poll, estimated that the President of the Government performs his duties rather poorly than well.
13 percent of respondents trust or rely heavily on Ferenc Gyurcsány, while Viktor Orbán has the support of 38 percent of respondents.
54 percent of the population doesn’t trust the head of government at all, and 27 percent don’t trust the president of the Young Democrats Alliance.
One indicator of the shaping of the political situation is that, what proportion of society thinks it is possible to control the discontent experienced in front of the person of the Head of Government without a change of government.
While after the October riots last year 35 percent felt it would be desirable to keep the government and the head of government in power, currently this proportion is only 20 percent, while the relative majority (33 percent) believe that the only solution is to hold new elections.
Interest in the referendum is characterized by the fact that 60 percent of respondents to the participation question answered that they would surely participate and another 20 percent said they are likely to participate.
By comparison, in "a general election to be held this Sunday" would certainly only 55 percent of the population and another 15 percent believe likely their participation. Based on the current intentions of the voters there is no doubt of the result of the popular consultation.
74 percent of the population would disapprove of paying for school fees, 79 percent for medical consultations and 84 percent for hospital care.
If we look at these proportions only among confident participants in the referendum, 81, 84, and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of education fees, payment for medical consultations, and hospital care.
The most expensive is the Auchan, the Tesco has quintupled its prices
The Budaörs gold trading triangle hypermarkets maintained the average price level increase of 16 percent, with the difference that VAT has not been increased this year.
Article by Napi Gazdaság
This year also increased by an average of 16 percent in the gold trading triangle of Budaörs the usual Christmas basket of the Napi newspaper, but in all hypermarkets there was a growth well above 1000 HUF.
As prices in food supermarkets had already been “triggered” in December last year, so there was no drastic percentage increase compared to the high starting point.
However, it is obviously frightening for consumers that what they were able to buy last year at a price well below HUF 9,000, today they can’t do it for even ten thousand.
The Napi basket in the hypermarkets studied exceeded the psychological limit of ten thousand HUF by a minimum of 91 HUF.
And the highest value basket was 10,573 HUF.
(In 2003 this basket cost 6,800 HUF.)
The price of Unicum liquor and fish remained almost at the level of the previous year, but there was a sharp increase in turkey breast fillet, nut and poppy seed.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed data from the Central Bureau of Statistics, although in Auchan we also found a kilo of bread for the price of 139 HUF.
The competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than 200 HUF.
It was also surprising at this store that the price of Coca-Cola with redimentable two-liter bottle cost less than 200 HUF, so this product, even with the price of the bottle, cost as little as 257 HUF.
However, in Napi Auchan’s basket it was the most expensive, while Cora was the cheapest.
According to our calculations, compared to last year’s Christmas prices, Cora rose by 15, while Tesco and Auchan rose by about 18 percent to Napi’s basket prices.
Comparing the values of last year’s most expensive basket with that of this year’s cheapest basket, the difference has been 12 percent, while growth between last year’s cheapest and this year’s most expensive one has been 21 percent.
The average growth was 1480 HUF.
Last year the average price growth was 1206 HUF, so that during Christmas last year prices were felt the increase in VAT.
It was precisely this process that shattered trade that supermarkets were visibly unable to make a decision on the price margin to be applied for each product and to calculate the effect of the price change on consumption.
(If the trader badly plans the speed of a product’s circulation, they may lose a significant profit on the margin that fits the sales volume.)
The increase in the price of the Napi basket reached such extremes as a result of the increase in VAT, which was the most expensive with 1720 HUF above the value recorded in 2006, while in the cheapest the difference was only 844 HUF.
This year there were no such extremes, since the highest price of now has been 1630 HUF more than last year and the cheapest also increased with 1284 HUF.
Comparing the two Christmas seasons, there was catastrophic price growth in less than 20 months, in hypermarkets the price of basic consumer goods grew by more than 30 percent.
(However, this does not necessarily confirm the figures of the Central Bureau of Statistics: this office, in the case of some basic foodstuffs, recorded in the 12-month interval a price increase of more than 30 percent.
So, for example, in addition to wheat, also in the case of egg.)
According to the Napi basket, in the latter case this seems almost impossible, since in the price of this product that was quite expensive already last year compared to the base, it was recorded, in the worst case only a 10% increase in prices.
According to all the indices, the flour suppliers have a stronger position than those of eggs, being able to impose the drastic increase in prices even on multinationals.
Hypermarkets do not complain about the gold trading triangle, they constantly talk about positive results.
According to our experience, most consumers in the three stores visited are no longer interested in prices.
Of all the products they buy large quantities, with preserved food being carried by pallets.
On Wednesday morning, the three stores formed large queues in front of the boxes because the number of customers suddenly increased.
However, we have information that in the interior of the country the sales volumes are lower, many multinationals complain to the polling institutes because the income is below their plans and not only in the case of food, but also in the case of appliances.
In many hospitals it is saved with disinfectants
This year several thousand infections have been registered in hospitals, primarily caused by the misuse of antibiotics.
The hygienic circumstances prevailing in hospitals, overcrowding of beds and overloading of staff do not favor the control of infections, says the chief medical officer of the National Center for Epidemiology.
In many hospitals it is saved even with disinfectants.
Recently, a MRSA infection has been diagnosed in the trauma department of János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of the antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of infection occurred in this same hospital earlier this year.
One injured in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient soon after had to return to the hospital as a result of the MRSA infection and since then a major surgical intervention has not been possible due to the presence of the bacteria in his body.
Until December 10 this year, 1094 cases of hospital infection caused by multidrug-resistant agents have been registered in the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System - said Karolina Böröcz, chief medical officer of the department of the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that the number of infections caused by multidrug-resistant agents has been safely recorded in hospitals, otherwise no information is available.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, resistant to methicillin-oxacilin.
A third of humans carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without causing any disease.
Infections caused by AS (e.g., throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once applied exaggeratedly or improperly to antibiotics, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics become highly antibiotic-resistant bacteria and spread quickly in inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, such as wound infections or sepsis in the first place to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, patients with the weakened organism, the elderly or underweight people.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of the János Hospital there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are everyday in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Resistant to antibiotics
"These patients are isolated, nurses take care of them in rubber gloves and mask and there are the right antibiotics for their treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are pre-screened for the presence of MRSA in their body, but even then infection cannot be prevented in all cases.
It is not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent hospital-based MRSA infections in most cases, however current national hospital circumstances do not favor the prevention of formation and contagion with multidrug-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate the diseases that carry MRSA in their bodies.
However, in Hungarian hospitals it is not fashionable to take microbiological samples.
This is also because the National Health Fund does not fund these medical tests.
So most cases come to light when already visible MRSA infections occur in the patient," said the epidemiological center's chief medical officer.
The European Union makes rigorous commendations for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological conditions.
Efforts must be made to target antibiotic therapy, i.e. microbiological tests should be done to prevent drug resistance from occurring, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological sampling is even less frequent in the case of ambulant patients or in basic care - said Karolina Böröcz.
It is saved with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is spread from one patient to another through healthcare personnel.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of rubber gloves and masks play a very important role, however also in this sense considerable faults are experienced in hospitals.
MRSA is spread through droplet transmission and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated at least by a distance of 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately you can also experience - added Karolina Böröcz - that in hospitals of less favorable economic situation is saved with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and that is why there is a greater probability for infection.
In the opinion of Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate preventive measures are followed, fewer such infections are recorded or the infection of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government Program Against MRSA
Treating the MRSA infection is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so it is being fought in every country.
In England, for example, there is a government program to prevent and reduce MRSA cases.
Apparently the program is successful, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multidrug-resistant agents (including MRSA) and hospital infections due to these pathogens.
Negative alcohol control of the police commander who caused a fatal accident
The official expert report on the case of the fatal accident caused by the police commander of district XXII has been made.
The possibility that he was driving drunk or in a stunned state can be ruled out by the then resigned district police commander XXII, who on Tuesday ran over and caused the death of a passerby - reported Friday Attila Morvai, spokesman for the General Prosecutor's Office of the Capital, after the expert report on the case had been prepared.
The expert report confirmed the result of the primary control of alcohol which had already found that the former police commander did not drink alcohol before getting behind the wheel.
The then head of the police station of the XXII district, on Tuesday with his private vehicle by turning to Kossuth Lajos Street of the XXII district, ran over a 55-year-old man, who intended to cross the street, but not in the designated area for pedestrians.
(This last fact, that is, the pedestrian did not use the zebra to cross the street, according to the regulations of the Traffic Code are not mitigating circumstances, the driver must always give way when bending.)
The passerby lost his life after being hospitalized.
The district police chief resigned and requested his retirement, according to the police statement, because he was deeply moved by the case.
The investigation of the case is carried out by the Budapest Prosecutor's Office.
Attila Morvai also said the former police commander from the start collaborated with prosecutors tasked with the investigation.
400 million euros more for infrastructure
Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and European Investment Bank (EIB) Vice President Marta Gajecka signed on Friday in Budapest three credit limit agreements worth a total of 400 million euros to finance education, transport and environmental infrastructures, as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of EUR 300 million to finance in the Hungarian budget the transport and environmental protection projects, to be carried out by the subsidy of the Cohesion Funds, of which the parties had previously signed a credit agreement worth 100 million, the contract just signed refers to the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million loan contract is also earmarked to finance the budget for educational projects.
The EIB approved a total of EUR 300 million for this Hungarian objective, on the use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be decided later, by extending the loan contract.
The parties signed a contract for 50 million euros for innovations, which the budget will mainly use for the innovations and research project of the University of Debrecen.
During the talks they also covered the issue of the construction of the 4th line of the Metro.
The agreement was reached that by the time Hungary finalizes the details of the Metro’s financing with the EU, they will revisit the issue of whether or not the original contract should be amended and how to do so.
According to János Veres, this may take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990 the EIB has financed a total of EUR 8.4 billion of projects in Hungary.
The interest on the credits is adjusted to the EURIBOR and the EIB offers an 8-year grace period, without charge for keeping the credit available to the debtor.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
Admirable is the development of the Bulgarian real estate market - the attention of all of Europe is directed towards that Balkan country just mentioned.
What, where and who are buying in the even cheaper EU market, which will quickly become more expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
The preferred target for real estate acquisitions in Eastern Europe is undoubtedly Bulgaria, with its cheap ski slopes apartments and beach chalets.
The mountainous regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are the most preferred, while in the Albena beaches, the "Golden Coast", the "Costa del Sol", the ancient Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people look for properties also in the surroundings of Kavarna and Balchik.
According to Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, sooner or later the central area of the country - such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - will arouse the interest of real estate developers and more and more people will buy real estate in the especially cheap area of Rus.
In the same way, the capital Sofia can be attractive, commercial and office spaces promise a rapid recovery of investment.
Bulgaria is on the best path to becoming one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe, thus being a highlight destination also during the other two seasons, in addition to summer and winter.
Therefore, cautious investors are already making their purchases, for example in the vicinity of Bansko.
In the opinion of analysts, those who buy real estate in Bulgaria, also strive to change their life and way of life.
The majority of customers are English, but they also come from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly from Romania.
Also present are the Maltese and Cypriot promoters and traditionally there are many Russian customers on the Black Sea beaches and ski paradises.
Foreign clients can be classified into three groups - says Georgi Jankov, regional director of Re/Max in Bulgaria.
Those who intend to settle here buy new or renovated properties for a price between 50 and 100 thousand euros or old houses in poor condition between 5 and 15 thousand euros, to renovate them later.
They require good communication and access, and for them it is important to be close to a large city, shops and usually a local doctor.
The second category consists of buyers of chalets (Bulgaria in December was included in the top 10 holiday destinations of the Germans).
The third group are real estate investors who make their purchases in the hope of benefiting in the medium or long term.
The price of capital real estate is constantly growing, as demand is increasing.
Although in the European Union Bulgaria has the lowest real estate prices, in the last five years these have suffered an annual increase of 21 percent.
The increase in the price of real estate considerably exceeds the growth of wages.
Fodor and the Six by Hundreds of Hungarians
As reported by the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor the meetings at the expert level will end on Tuesday and on Wednesday after the official inauguration will continue the negotiations at the level of ministers on the international climate regime after 2012.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world are deliberating on the Bali Roadmap, which provides for efforts after the emissions reduction period, established by the Kyoto Protocol, in force until 2012.
Lively discussions are currently taking place between developing and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that at the moment it does not want to negotiate on precise figures, although it tends to agree that compared to the 1990 situation, until 2020 the emission of the gases responsible for the greenhouse effect will decrease by 25 to 40 percent.
Another major theme of the conference is whether or not industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing to offer material and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement was also reached on the aid to be offered to developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be run by a 16-member board of directors, likely within the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF).
Six Hundreds of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU’s efforts to retain its leading role in global climate protection and promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The minister said the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 2020, compared to the 1990 level, regardless of whether or not the “post-2012 agreement” will be signed, and is willing to commit to a reduction of up to 30 percent if the world’s other major developed regions and developing countries are also willing to make commitments in line with their responsibilities and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the signatory countries to the 1997 Kyoto Protocol pledged to decrease by 5.2 percent, within this the then 15 EU member states pledged to meet an 8 percent decrease.
Hungary’s commitment is to cut greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent over the period 1985-87, which our country will meet.
There is a lot at stake in Bali, since in two years the international agreement on long-term climate policy will have to be signed, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed until after 2012. In this case the reduction commitments, assumed in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international system of emission reductions, whose need was warned in the most recent international partnership of the IPCC.
With this, the reduction of emissions would suffer a delay and a rise of more than 2°C in the average temperature of the Earth could not be prevented, a fact that according to scientists would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
British Army recruits on YouTube
British Army units in a video distributor publish footage of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First the British Air Force (RAD) took advantage of YouTube services: special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos about their actions against the Taliban, the BBC reported.
These recordings made with mini-cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled in Kandahar's general operating body, then sent to London for upload to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable.
Already 139 recordings from air force soldiers have been uploaded to the Internet in this way and its "channel" has already been seen by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered in the spring of 2007 under the name of "defence headquarters" and publishes videos of both actions perpetrated in Iraq and Afghanistan, while both the Ministry of the Commonwealth Office and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had uploaded the videos for recruitment purposes, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defense they also serve to present to the public the true objective of the presence of the British army abroad.
This type of propaganda costs practically nothing compared to conventional television recruitment spots, defense expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC, but they inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the raison d’être of the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans made a video game.
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the carefully edited and censored recordings, amateur videos also appear on the distributor, for example on the deaths of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers speak as much as possible of losses, without however presenting the bloody part of the fights.
In addition, numerous videos recorded in real operations have been uploaded to the Internet from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British army is only recently seizing this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different form of recruitment with free-to-download video games called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can put himself directly in place of the soldiers.
