The forces of the giant strike are gathering
The League Unions and the National Federation of Workers’ Commissions will set up a strike commission on Friday to coordinate Monday’s strike that will last indefinitely.
A protest rally will be held on Saturday, while on Monday – the day on which the final vote on the public health law will be held – work stoppage will begin.
This action will certainly cause great difficulties in transport, since rail traffic will be completely stopped and until 13 hours workers of the Budapest Collective Transport Company will also be on strike.
On Friday afternoon, the League Unions will report on the details of Monday’s strike that will be held jointly with the National Federation of Workers’ Commissions.
The strike commission of the LIGA and the National Union of Machinists will also be constituted, which will coordinate Monday’s actions.
A protest rally will be held on Saturday, while participating unions will strike indefinitely on Monday if no agreement is reached with the government.
This means that - on the day of the parliamentary vote on the public health law - they did not report on the date of the end of the strike initiated.
If the National Assembly disapproves of the public health law, the unions will immediately withdraw their call for strikes.
Instead, if the law is passed, strike committees will meet and decide on the future.
On the basis of the National Assembly’s Monday agenda, it is also possible to vote only on the public health law in the late hours of the night, or at least near midnight.
As a result of the strike that will start on Monday, there will be significant difficulties in transport: railways will be stopped indefinitely, in the morning a part of public transport in Budapest and more than half of the intercity bus transport of Volán companies may be stopped.
Simultaneously, in many parts of the country, half of the roads will be closed.
Numerous unions and civil organizations have joined the strike, their names are constantly updated on the League’s website.
Some unions announced their strike indefinitely, others for a definite time.
Until Thursday afternoon the State Railway and the Free Trade Union of Railway Workers (SLTF) could not reach an agreement even on the minimum services, although, as the Christmas holidays approach, more and more people travel on trains.
According to information received so far, from the beginning of the day until 1 p.m. workers of the Budapest Collective Transport Company will be on strike, Budapest Airports from 7 a.m. to 9 a.m., will hold a four-hour strike the LIGA Trade Unions of the Electrical and Thermal Energy Industry, the Educators’ Trade Unions called for a strike of 2 a.m. and the 8 a.m.
The Hungarian Association of Physicians will pronounce on national strike at alternative times and the Democratic Union of Health and Social Workers (SDTSSS) that are part of the Forum for Trade Union Cooperation, will hold a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands made by the League is for the government to withdraw its proposal on public health reform and submit a new conception to a social debate.
The second demand is that they gradually introduce the new way of calculating pensions that will come into force next year.
The third is to ensure, even before 2010, in the case of advanced pensions the possibility that the occupations that deserve it can enter the system.
The fourth reason for the strike is that the Free Trade Union of Railway Workers (SLTF), which is part of the League Trade Unions, do not accept the proposal of the Ministry of Economy and Transport on the railway sidelines and expect another different proposal.
Political Capital[b1]: The country increases the risk by the Hungarian Guard
According to the Political Capital’s Risk Analyzing Division, the activity of the Hungarian Guard, set up in August this year with the support of the Better Hungary Movement, has increased the political risk of Hungary and the region from various points of view.
The company's "risk warning" states: "In relation to the activity of the Hungarian Guard, the greatest political risk is the fact that with the escalation of ethnic tensions between the gypsy and non-gypsy population of Hungary, even in the short term, violent ethnic clashes may occur."
The main reason for this is that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is probably the provocation of an event of this nature, added the representative of the research institute.
They affirmed that all this is due to one of the main faults of the protagonists of Hungarian political life: "the protagonists of public life gave the public debate of the gypsy problem to the representatives of radical and extremist political groups, who were able to base their political strategy on the existing discrepancies between gypsies and Hungarians".
This aggravates the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts breaking out.
In addition, according to the research institute, the activity of the National Guard, as a result of the great attention of the national and international media, "significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of the stability and democratic development of the country."
They remind us that since the autumn of 2006 the reorganization of radical and far-right groups in Hungary has received increasing publicity and momentum and that since the summer of 2007 numerous organizations have been formed in the country that define themselves as "associations of national self-defense".
“The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as civil organizations, while openly proclaiming the training of their members for defense – even armed – (civil defense, national defense, defense of public order), alluding to the ineptitudes of the police, of the army, that is, of the state.”
They asserted: all this occurs in accordance with the method that attempts to give a civil presentation to different political aspirations, based on society’s discontent with politics and political parties.
Highlighting the civil and the form of association in the case of these associations not only serves to avoid the legal problems of legal registration, but is at the same time also a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activity of the Hungarian Guard is also a risk factor from the point of view of neighbourly relations.
