Party is not always written with red numbers
In Hungary the law precisely defines the days that are written with red numbers on the calendar and it has already become a widespread practice that around holidays - which next year will be less - workdays are reorganized.
Even in the EU and North America, the holidays are not unitary.
Hungarian laws make a difference between national holidays, state holidays and public holidays.
The festive days are mainly related to religious festivals and historical ephemeris.
Let us celebrate the New Year too: both the last day of the old year, and the first day of the new year is festive - the latter especially so that you may rest those who have spent celebrating the old year.
Throughout the year we have eleven parties written with red numbers on the calendar.
It is a national holiday on March 15 in memory of the revolution of 1848 and on October 23, commemorating the revolution of 1956.
On August 20th we celebrate the foundation of the State, on May 1st we celebrate Labor Day, on November 1st and 2nd we remember our deceased family and friends.
In addition, in our country there are two-day feasts of Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
According to the calendar, our state, national or religious holidays rarely coincide with a weekend, so it often bridges when there is only one working day before or after the holiday.
In exchange for the extended weekends thus, during the previous Saturdays you cannot be absent from work or school.
It is the minister of labor who regulates in his specific decree when it is necessary to work exactly in exchange for the day directly before or after the feast.
This legal standard is mandatory for all employers and their employees, as well as for employees and public officials.
It is not mandatory for companies and service institutions that, due to their role, work continuously even during holidays.
This year the work order can be changed only around the holidays of the end of the year: from December 24 practically stops life in the country, since according to experiences, most people "bridge" during the days between Christmas and the end of the year or take their holidays during these days.
Next year several of our holidays will coincide with mid- or weekends, so there will be fewer changes in working days than this year.
First the agenda around the Labor Day will be modified so that then, for four successive days, workers can rest.
On Saturday, April 26 will be a working day, so that in return Friday, May 2 will be a holiday.
The other change is related to the party of October 23: on Saturday, October 18, you will have to work instead of Friday, October 24.
On the other hand, the next year during the holiday will be able to rest, since from December 24 it will not work almost anywhere, even if the last day of the year is a Wednesday.
Six Small Disincentives to Bitter Your Colleagues’ Lives
Emails that we forget to send, sound messages that we never receive, innocent lies that pass on to us without us noticing: they are all part of our everyday folklore at work.
Decide whether to adapt to small inconveniences or consciously avoid confusing situations that can irritate others.
Advice.
“Sorry, I forgot to let you know you were picked up from the marketing department,” one of your colleagues said.
That's why you didn't go on a date?
At best, he’s sorry and tries to fix the issue, perhaps calling the marketing department to tell them that he forgot to deliver the message to you (this is the least common solution).
Most of the time the matter is resolved by apologizing.
Before you go on with nasty explanations, it’s worth meditating on the things you can make your colleagues’ lives bitter and consciously strive to avoid them.
Do you borrow something that is not yours?
There’s nothing more annoying than when you want to grab a document, office supplies, or your phone and you can’t find them.
Remember yesterday you put the stapler on the table, but this morning it's gone?
Can you find your lost pen on the table of one of your colleagues?
Don’t take anything away from your colleagues without asking them, because they will rightly be angry with you for stealing their stuff.
Do not pick up envelopes or post-it from the office because it can be unpleasant when you need them immediately and they run out ahead of time.
Do you gossip about the privacy of your colleagues?
There is no good solution to stop rumors that are already running.
Who, what is he doing and with whom?
Where and why?
Don’t pass on to everyone the information (suggestions) you have about the private lives of your colleagues!
Don’t abuse your colleague’s trust when he shares his innermost secrets with you!
Bury in yourself what you have heard and do not gossip about your colleague in his absence, although others also know the things about him.
Are you going on sick leave unjustifiably?
When you call the office on the phone and say you’re sick and your head hurts unbearably, you feel bad or good, you feel like that day you prefer to rest; think that others must do your work, your impassable tasks, your work for good.
Don't bother your colleague!
If you already know in advance that the next day you will not go to the office or something can happen to you, so you will have to stay at home, tell them, so that your colleagues or your boss do not have to face your absence the next day.
Landings, laughs, phone calls
Are you involved in your work, but are you suddenly taken out of it by your colleagues’ chuckles?
Have you unintentionally heard a phone call that would have been better not to hear?
Don’t bother your colleagues with your chanting, singing, loud conversations (less when you do them above their head), kicking, constant blasphemies, expressing your discontents aloud.
All of these can be annoying, even if they aren’t delving into a project right now (writing, planning, organizing).
Do you blame others for a mistake?
Don’t blame others if you haven’t finished something in time, you forgot to send an important letter or message!
Don’t allude to the chaos eventually reigning in the office, or the noise your colleagues make!
You must recognize if you have made a mistake that harms others and you must make amends for the mistake!
Ask how you can repair your fault!
Do you feel at home in the office?
Jogging and slippers: very comfortable habit for the house, but not suitable for the office!
Do not wear a comfortable jog even if your occupation allows it!
Don’t get messed up, respect your colleagues and yourself by wearing everyday clothes, elegant and beautiful when your occupation requires it!
