A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Bad Arolsen Nazi archives, which describe the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are freely accessible.
The 47 million archival documents, stored over 27 km of shelves in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were hitherto not available only for a “humanitarian” purpose, i.e. individually and nominatively, at the request of a former victim or his rightful persons.
The eleven states in charge of its management – such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States – agreed in May 2006 to open them up to seekers and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
Historians’ access to Bad Arolsen will allow for research “particularly on the displacements of prisoners, the population of the camps and the health status of the forced laborers,” explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Commission of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, such as Germany, objected to the openness to the public of these nominative documents, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the alleged homosexuality or mental handicap of certain victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or detention orders established by the Gestapo had been gathered after the war for a practical purpose: to find the peasants deported or subjected to compulsory work and, eventually, to provide them with proof of their internment, in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees process tens of thousands of individual petitions.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
“There is nothing fundamentally new to be expected from these documents,” said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for Research on Antisemitism at the Technische Universität Berlin in 2006.
