What insurance is right for me?
Car insurance, which covers the driver in case of possible accidents, represents a significant expense that will depend on various factors, such as age, sex, age of the card, marital status, the type of vehicle to be insured or the use of it, among others.
Having a car is just the beginning.
Choosing the right car insurance is even more difficult than choosing the right model.
First of all, we need to be clear about what we are talking about.
Car insurance is an agreement between an insurance company and the insured.
This commitment is embodied in an insurance contract, which stipulates that the company receives the amount of the agreed premium in exchange for being held liable for the obligation to pay compensation in the event of a claim.
The premium is the price of the insurance, which is established taking into account various factors, such as age, sex, age of the card, marital status, the type of vehicle to be insured or the use given to it, among others.
Insurance companies set their prices based on statistics, so that the higher the likelihood of an accident, the higher the fee to pay.
That’s why both women and over 25s have to pay lower premiums, as statistics show they have a lower accident rate because of their prudence.
Also, taking advantage of the counts, companies have come to the conclusion that married people tend to have fewer accidents than single drivers.
The use given to the vehicle will influence the frequency, and with it the likelihood of having some kind of accident.
Increasing the frequency increases the odds.
There are many variables that insurers take into account when setting the premium price.
Therefore, the driver must study the situation well to choose the car insurance that best suits his profile.
We will expose here the most significant variables when choosing one or another type of insurance, so that it, in addition to adapting to the characteristics of the insured, offers a reasonable price.
Young people under the age of 25 are faced with various drawbacks when it comes to hiring insurance at an affordable price, such as reduced driving experience and the age of the card.
Although the ideal way to be well insured is full-risk insurance, there are other, more economical options.
More cautious drivers can opt for a full-risk franchise, so they get full-risk insurance coverage but at a more feasible price.
This kind of agreement would require the customer to pay a portion of the amount of the claim.
“The part of the amount of the claim that the customer contributes will be preset based on the value of the premium, which will be higher the lower the amount,” says Luis Noguera, head of First Europe in Spain, an online insurance broker.
Another option is extended third party insurance, so that the customer ensures protection against damage caused to third parties, although not to those caused in their own car.
In addition, it would be covered by theft, fire and loss of the vehicle.
One piece of advice.
If you are under 25 years old try to be careful and avoid claims as much as possible, as this will have an impact on the bonus, being able to reduce the cost of insurance in the future.
A bonus is a reduction on the base rate that the company owns.
On the contrary, a penalty is a surcharge on that base rate.
“Bonus and penalties will depend on the company and the company’s benefit.
If the company has had a good year, it can afford to increase the bonuses,” Noguera explains.
After the age of 25, drivers have it easier when it comes to insurance, since the accident rate is reduced thanks to the accumulated experience.
For this reason, it is best to hire an all-risk franchise.
“Normally young people cannot make use of the experience previously acquired when using themselves in an accident, and even when driving,” says the director in Spain of the European company, adding that most accidents occur in the second year of driving, once the ‘novice fear’ has passed.
However, if the client is married but still has no children, it is preferable that he negotiates full-risk insurance, as long as his financial situation allows it, of course.
For their part, marriages with children are considered by insurers as the public with the lowest accident rate, so the surcharges will be lower.
In this case the best insurance would be one with a deductible (may be 300 euros), or, when a high level of bonus is available, one to third parties extended from the third year of life of the vehicle.
“They drive more relaxed and have greater purchasing power to afford to take on a larger amount of franchise,” says Luis Noguera.
For retirees it is advisable to have a full-risk insurance with franchise (being this one of 150 euros), or one extended to third parties when you have a high level of bonus.
It must be said that car insurance is important, not only because it covers the driver in case of possible accidents, but also because it represents a significant expense, which is why it is essential to properly study the insurance that best suits us according to our personal situation.
