Is the subprime mortgage crisis infecting the U.S. credit card market?
When there is blood in the water, it is natural for dorsal fins to swim excited around.
Today, with the American housing market in crisis, predators have their eyes set on the credit card market in the country.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs estimate that credit card losses can reach $99 million if the subprime mortgage crisis infects other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of infection are already seen.
There is an increase in both card charges and crime rates, which measures the proportion of balances that have not been amortized or that are more than 30 days late respectively.
HSBC announced last month that it has taken 1.4 million in charge of its U.S. consumer financing business, in part due to weakness in card borrowers.
However, it is too early for panic.
Delinquency and crime are at low levels.
According to Moody’s, a rating agency, the third quarter crime rate of 3.89% was almost a percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be explained in part by technical factors.
A change in the U.S. Bankruptcy Act (2005) resulted in a sharp drop in bankruptcy claims, which in turn represent a large loss in credit cards; the number of claims (and therefore, of default) would be growing again, or it could happen that conditions for borrowers were getting worse.
The industry also reports strong payout rates, which show how much of their debts consumers pay each month.
And trust in credit cards and asset-backed securities is pretty firm, despite paralysis in other financial areas.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research firm, predicts that emission volumes by 2007 will be about 25% higher than last year.
The direct channels of crisis infection between subprime mortgages and the credit card market certainly exist: consumers like to charge debts to credit cards now that credit institutions are expiring.
But credit card issuers look more at the flow of liquidity than at active securities, so falling prices don’t necessarily trigger a change in borrowers’ creditworthiness.
They can even work to benefit the issuers.
Incentives for consumers to continue amortizing the mortgage decreases if properties are worth less than the value of the loan; and as a result, the payment of the card debt rises on the priority list.
Card issuers can also respond quickly and flexibly to the difficult conditions that mortgage lenders face by changing interest rates or altering credit balances.
That in theory should reduce the risk of rapid asset retrenchment.
“We’re not going to wake up one day and reassess all the loans,” says Gary Perlin, head of finance at Capital One.
If a sudden subprime infection in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained decline are much more real.
If home prices are lower and a credit contraction pushes America into recession, the industry undoubtedly faces a tougher future.
We have to keep an eye on those dorsal fins.
