Venus: Earth's twin brother.
Although its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the most Earth-like planet, something that until now had not been raised. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and swirls at the poles, the same ones that also appear in winter on Earth.
For three decades, researchers had suspected that there might be lightning on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it has discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus the rays quiet from a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, says Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles to the scientific journal "Nature".
According to Urey-Miller’s famous model of the origin of life, lightning caused life on Earth: storms could have triggered reactions in the ocean that, in turn, would have given rise to amino acids that are the building blocks of life.
On Venus it is not so: if there were ever life there, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there can be no life on the surface of Venus: the atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and temperatures of 500°C reign on the surface, oscillating in such a way that temperatures below zero can be reached.
"Possibly, Venus is a 'devil' twin of Earth, but it's still a twin," Russell said.
The main objective of the Venus Express mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so similar to Earth in its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since there were no special missions since the 1990s, just for research of this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for the research of Venus.
The latest results of the research to be presented in many “Nature” papers, according to the researchers, underline not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
"This also demonstrates that neighboring planets have more features in common with Earth than we had previously assumed," ESA reports.
Despite the already known stormy winds at the North Pole, researchers discovered in the southern polar region also a vortex formed by the faster-spinning clouds.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of wind flows in the high atmospheric layers of the Earth’s poles, as described by a team of researchers from Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet in the Solar System has a mass almost equal to the Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers it is almost as large.
This planet is also called a sunrise star or evening star orbiting the Sun for almost 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day on Venus equals 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bar does not closely resemble Earth, scientists assume that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
On both planets water had clustered which on Earth remained in the oceans, but on Venus it dissociated into the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had become carbon stones, on Venus it forms most of the atmosphere.
