It's not the wooden boxes.
Whoever connects the terms Sweden and wooden box, thinks of Ikea, but does not think of Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently the wooden boxes produced in Sweden are like the shadow that weighs on Warhol’s list of works.
Most of the ninety-four "type" Brightness-Boxes on this list are fake.
After a few months ago the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo-Boxes, the Moderna Museet museum in Stockholm carried out internal research and came to disappointing conclusions: the six "Brillo-Boxes", which the former museum director Pontus Hultén gave to the Moderna Museum in Stockholm, are also a fake of the other hundred.
Prehistory is too complicated with a confusing relationship between artistic and sponsored productions.
In 1964 Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York, painted the wooden boxes in red, blue and white, with the same sample that had "Brillo" soap powder cartons.
According to Warhol, in the exhibition of his 1968 works at the Moderna Museet museum were exhibited hundreds of Bright-cartons. These were not made by Warhol (because of the expenses), but were brought directly from the "Brillo" cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but examples (which were only objects) exhibited.
In the same year, 1968, Warhol allowed to produce in Sweden some shiny wooden boxes, but they were not exhibited at the Modern Museet Museum.
Witnesses of those times now speak of almost fifteen boxes, which at that time entered the history of art and auctions as originals of the "Brillo-Boxes" of "Stockhol type" authorized by Andy Warhol.
At auction some of them were purchased for more than $100,000.
The problem is that after the famous director of the Pontus Hultén museum made false statements that in 1968 in Sweden were produced and exposed almost a hundred of the wooden boxes that Warhol left to him.
But in reality, 105 boxes were produced in the same year in 1990 in Malmö for Hultén and for the exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, the head of the Moderna Museet museum curators, investigated six Brillo-Boxes owned by the museum and also three of the Swedish private property that were manufactured in 1968 in Stockholm. They first printed and ground their tight silvers and then painted them in oil with the brush.
On the contrary, the structure of the 1990 copies shows that the paint was applied with a roller without directly printing the tight silvers.
