Rebel soldiers surrender in Manila.
In the Philippines, rebel soldiers who had entrenched themselves in a Manila hotel and demanded the fall of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo have surrendered.
Chief Antonio Trillanes, who blames the president for corruption and electoral fraud, told a reporter that he could not answer for shedding blood.
Soldiers loyal to the government had assaulted the hotel using tear gas.
Nearly two hundred soldiers had been entrenched in the building for a few hours.
Almost half of them, including Trillanes, were on trial on Thursday for attempting a coup in 2003 that ended in a failure.
He took advantage of the negotiations, so that he could suddenly settle down with about 30 supporters.
Evidently the military police who were to watch him had passed into their ranks and followed their riot.
They entered the "Peninsula" hotel and demanded the fall of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Government troops blocked the neighborhood around the Noble Hotel.
The president called for an urgent session of the Security Cabinet.
Norberto Gonzales, the national security adviser, condemned the soldiers’ behavior.
“People are fed up,” Trillanes said.
“We invite people to join our ranks.”
General Danilo Lim, who had previously led the elite Scout Reangers troops, said that soon the other military troops wanted to follow suit.
Major government critics on Thursday called for a major demonstration against the president.
His government has been criticized for corruption for months.
In 2003 the financial district in Manila was a site that attracted all the attention for the riot that was attempted against Arroyo.
The uprising failed after about 24 hours because the army wanted to participate.
Since 1986, there have been at least seven coup attempts against the democratically elected government in the Philippines.
United Internet will be Versatel’s largest shareholder.
United Internet secured more than 20 percent of the shares of telecommunications company Versatel.
On Wednesday, the company reported that the average price for a share is 14.46 euros.
It has only 20.05 percent of the share capital.
There was a lot of speculation about the company’s uptake.
There are also options to further increase the financial share at Versatel.
United Internet reported that with this step it wants to accelerate the consolidation of the German DSL (Digital Subscriber Line) market.
On Wednesday, they made assumptions about entering the business, after the bank Brendenberg increased its stake in the Duesseldorf network operator by 5 percent to 15.1 percent.
In the financial market this means that the financial institution maintains the equity securities for a third-party partner.
United Internet already the day before involved with almost 10 percent the telecom company Drillisch.
Drillisch placed 17.4 million of the new shares with a value of 106.4 million euros.
United Internet has bought 5.15 million shares of them for 31.4 million euros.
In addition, the companies started with negotiations on commercialization cooperations for DSL-products.
“We strengthen our collaboration,” said a spokesman for United Internet.
The two companies founded an MSP joint venture, to acquire the competitor Freenet.
On Thursday, United Internet reported that at first, the two companies want to be happy with the ten percent stake in Freenet and do not make use of their right, that is, they involve 18.49 percent of Freenet.
That meant both companies kept all the options, especially participation in the Freenet joint stock company.
Negotiations between United Internet and Freenet over a strategic partnership ended in mid-November.
This "game" with Freenet that will last for many months and is not very understandable is part of the consolidation of the German Telecom market.
At the end of the third quarter Freenet had 2.9 million customers with a mobile phone contract and 1.27 million with a DSL contract or a full contract.
United Internet and Drillisch’s holding company had 6.01 percent of the stake in Freenet.
Then they had agreed that Drillisch was going to get the other four percent.
The right to buy 18.49 percent of the investment company Vatas was already agreed in August.
